    <div id="wiki-content">
	
        <p>(Propositional logic continued)</p>
<h2 class="header"><i>1</i>Propositional arguments continued<a class="headerlink" href="#propositional-arguments-continued" name="propositional-arguments-continued">&para;</a></h2>
<h3 class="header"><i>1.1</i>Relating consistency and validity<a class="headerlink" href="#relating-consistency-and-validity" name="relating-consistency-and-validity">&para;</a></h3>
<p>A propositional argument is <strong>valid</strong> if the conclusion is true <em>every</em> time the premises are all true.</p>
<p>It is <strong>consistent</strong> if there <em>is</em> such a valuation <span>$V$</span>.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Proposition: <span>$\Phi_1, ... \Phi_n \vdash \Psi$</span> is valid <span>$\iff$</span> <span>$\{ \Phi_1, ... \Phi_n, \neg \Psi \}$</span> is inconsistent.</p>
<p>Proof: Suppose the left side is true. Then, for any valuation <span>$V$</span>, the left side 9A) implies the right side (B) if <span>$V(\Phi_1) = ... = V(\Phi_n) = \top$</span>. So <span>$V(\neg \Psi) = \bot$</span>. So yeah, inconsistent.</p>
<p>Now show that B implies A. Suppose B and <span>$V(\Phi_1) = ... = V(\Phi_n) = \top$</span>. By B, <span>$V(\neg \Phi) = \bot$</span> so <span>$V(\Phi) = \top$</span>. So A is correct, and so <span>$A \iff B$</span>. No idea what this proof is doing.</p>
</blockquote>
<h2 class="header"><i>2</i>Disjuncts and conjuncts<a class="headerlink" href="#disjuncts-and-conjuncts" name="disjuncts-and-conjuncts">&para;</a></h2>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Disjunctive normal form</strong>: conjunctive clauses<sup id="fnref:1"><a href="#fn:1" rel="footnote" title="A conjunction of literals. For example: $p \land q...">1</a></sup> joined by <span>$\lor$</span> (<span>$\Phi_1 \lor \Phi_2 \lor ... \lor \Phi_m$</span>)<sup id="fnref:2"><a href="#fn:2" rel="footnote" title="$m$ can be 1.">2</a></sup><br />
<strong>Conjunctive normal form</strong>: disjunctive clauses<sup id="fnref:3"><a href="#fn:3" rel="footnote" title="A disjunction of literals. For example: $p \lor q$...">3</a></sup> joined by <span>$\land$</span> (<span>$\Phi_1 \land \Phi_2 \land ... \land \Phi_m$</span>)<sup id="fnref:2"><a href="#fn:2" rel="footnote" title="$m$ can be 1.">2</a></sup></p>
</blockquote>
<p>A basic disjunct is sort of the opposite of what you'd expect - <span>$\alpha_1 \land \alpha_2 \land \alpha_k$</span> where <span>$\alpha$</span> is either <span>$\top$</span> or <span>$\bot$</span> or <span>$p$</span> or <span>$\neg p$</span> for some variable <span>$p$</span><sup>confirm</sup>. A basic conjunct is the above with the <span>$\land$</span>s replaced with <span>$\lor$</span>s.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.1</i>From truth tables to disjunctive normal forms<a class="headerlink" href="#from-truth-tables-to-disjunctive-normal-forms" name="from-truth-tables-to-disjunctive-normal-forms">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Given the following truth table for an unknown formula in conjunctive normal form<sup>confirm</sup> involving the variables <span>$(p, q, r)$</span>, it is possible to write out the formula in both disjunctive and conjunctive normal form:</p>
<table class="ui celled padded table">
<thead>
<tr>
<th><span>$p$</span></th>
<th><span>$q$</span></th>
<th><span>$r$</span></th>
<th><span>$\Phi(p, q, r)$</span></th>
</tr>
</thead>
