<p>In this case, there are three rows that come out <span>$\top$</span> and so there are three basic disjuncts, resulting in the following formula in d.n.f:</p>
<p><span>$$(p \land q \land \neg r) \lor (p \land \neg q \land \neg r) \lor (\neg p \land q \land r)$$</span></p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.2</i>Simplifying formulas in normal form<a class="headerlink" href="#simplifying-formulas-in-normal-form" name="simplifying-formulas-in-normal-form">&para;</a></h3>
<p>We can simplify formulas in disjunctive normal form by finding equivalent formulas. For example, we can simplify <span>$(p \land q \land \neg r) \lor (p \land \neg q \land \neg r)$</span> as <span>$(p \land \neg r)$</span>, which is a basic disjunct and which has the same truth table (the <span>$q$</span>s in the expanded form have merely been dropped, since we have both <span>$q$</span> and <span>$\neg q$</span>). I don't think we can simplify this example any more, so let's return to the first example:</p>
<p><span>$$[ (p \land \neg q \land r) \lor (p \land q \land r) ] \lor (p \land \neg q \land r) \lor (p \land \neg q \land \neg r) \lor (\neg p \land q \land r) \lor (\neg p \land \neg q \land r)$$</span></p>
<p><span>$$\therefore (p \land r) \lor (\neg p \land r) \lor (p \land \neg q)$$</span></p>
<p><span>$$\therefore r \lor (p \land \neg q)$$</span></p>
<p>(magic)</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.3</i>From disjunctive to conjunctive<a class="headerlink" href="#from-disjunctive-to-conjunctive" name="from-disjunctive-to-conjunctive">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Now let's turn the above into conjunctive normal form. We can use the distribute law for this, as follows:</p>
<p><span>$$r \lor (p \land \neg q) \iff (r \lor p) \land (r \lor \neg q)$$</span></p>
<p>which is in conjunctive normal form.</p>
<p>Now, consider <span>$(p \land q \land \neg r) \lor (\neg p \land q \land \neg r) \lor (\neg p \land \neg q \land \neg r)$</span> which is equivalent to <span>$(\neg p \land \neg r) \lor (q \land \neg r)$</span> which is equivalent to the negation of the first example<sup>confirm</sup>.</p>
<p>Using the de Morgan laws<sup id="fnref:4"><a href="#fn:4" rel="footnote" title="According to the de Morgan laws, the following two...">4</a></sup> we see that this is equivalent to <span>$\neg (p \land q \land \neg r) \land \neg (\neg p \land q \land \neg r) \land \neg (\neg p \land \neg q \land \neg r)$</span> (de Morgan laws used twice). This was found by applying the de Morgan laws to the ones that come out <span>$\bot$</span> in the truth table, and resulted in a conjunctive normal form, but the other way, with the distributive law, resulted in a shorter one. There's probably a simpler way using the truth table but I don't remember it right now<sup>later?</sup>.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.4</i>The universality of disjunctive and conjunctive normal forms<a class="headerlink" href="#the-universality-of-disjunctive-and-conjunctive-normal-forms" name="the-universality-of-disjunctive-and-conjunctive-normal-forms">&para;</a></h3>
<p>So we reach the following conclusion: any conceivable formula in any number of variables is equivalent to a formula in cnf as well as to a (different) formula in dnf. In particular, any formula is equivalent to a formula using only the connectives <span>$\land, \lor$</span> and <span>$\neg$</span>. In fact, we could even disperse with one of the binary connectives if we wanted, using the de Morgan laws.</p>
<p>This brings us to a more general conclusion. If any formula is equivalent to a formula using only <span>$\land$</span> and <span>$\neg$</span>, then the set <span>$\{ \land, \neg\}$</span> is functionally complete. We can even get rid of the propositional constants of <span>$\top$</span> and <span>$\bot$</span> if we liked, replacing them with <span>$p \lor \neg p$</span> and <span>$p \land \neg p$</span>, respectively. But the set <span>$\{ \land, \lor \}$</span> is <em>not</em> functionally complete, because no matter how many <span>$\land$</span>s and <span>$\lor$</span>s you use, if <span>$V(p) = \top$</span>, the whole thing comes out <span>$\top$</span>, no matter what.</p>
<p>But do we need two connectives to make a functionally complete set? Isn't there a connective that is functionally complete just by itself? In fact, there are several. One particular such connective is discussed in detail next lecture.</p>
<div class="footnote">
<div class="ui divider"></div>
<ol>
<li id="fn:1">
<p>A conjunction of literals. For example: <span>$p \land q$</span> or <span>$p$</span> or <span>$p \land q \land r$</span>.&#160;<a href="#fnref:1" rev="footnote" title="Jump back to footnote 1 in the text">&#8617;</a></p>
</li>
<li id="fn:2">
<p><span>$m$</span> can be 1.&#160;<a href="#fnref:2" rev="footnote" title="Jump back to footnote 2 in the text">&#8617;</a></p>
</li>
<li id="fn:3">
<p>A disjunction of literals. For example: <span>$p \lor q$</span> or <span>$p$</span> or <span>$p \lor q \lor r$</span>.&#160;<a href="#fnref:3" rev="footnote" title="Jump back to footnote 3 in the text">&#8617;</a></p>
</li>
<li id="fn:4">
<p>According to the de Morgan laws, the following two are equivalent: <span>$\neg (p \lor q)$</span> and <span>$(\neg p) \land (\neg q)$</span>&#160;<a href="#fnref:4" rev="footnote" title="Jump back to footnote 4 in the text">&#8617;</a></p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
	
